  "prompt": "Are non-living things made up of cells?",
  "response": "No, non-living things are not made up of cells. Cells are the basic structural and functional units of living organisms. Non-living things, such as rocks, water, and metals, do not have cellular structures and do not exhibit the characteristics of life, such as growth, reproduction, and response to stimuli. Living organisms, like plants, animals, and fungi, are composed of one or more cells, while non-living matter does not contain cells.",
